title: Mount Rainier
description: The most famous mountain in Washington State located in the Mount Rainier National Park. Rainier is also the highest mountain in the state and the tallest in the Cascade Volcanic Arc. Though dormant for a long time, the volcano has a high probability of eruption. The name Tahoma means 'Sky Wiper' or 'Snow-covered mountain'

title: Mount Adams
description: An active stratovolcano in the Cascade Mountain Range, also holding the title as the second highest mountain in Washington States. The mountain is named about President John Adams while its indigenous name means 'Standing Up' or 'High Mountain'.

title: Mount Baker
description: An active, glacier covered stratovolcano, with the second most active thermal crater second to Mt. St. Helens. Baker has the second heaviest glacier cover in Washington State while towering over Bellingham, Washington. The name Kulshan means 'shooting place' which refers to the hunting that was performed on the slopes of the mountain.

title: Glacier Peak
description: The fourth tallest peak in Washington state that is also the most isolated stratovolcano out the five in Washington. Glacier Peak is researched to be the most active volcano in the state, erupting five times in the last 3000 years.

title: Mount St. Helens
description: A prominent mountain in Washington state history after is massive eruption in 1980. St. Helens is named after a British diplomat, Alleyne FitzHerbert, 1st Baron St Helens, who was a friend of George Vancouver who surveyed the area in tha 18th century.

title: Bonanza Peak
description: Located east of the I-5, the peak is highest point in Chelan County and the highest non-volcanic peak in Washington State. The peak is located near Glacier Peak and the Wenatchee National Forest Park

title: Mount Stuart
description: Mount Stuart is the second highest non-volcanic peak in Washington state, holding the title of the tallest peak in teh Stuart Range. The peak can be found east Snoqualmie pass. It got its name from a Civil War Union officer George McCellan, who named in honor of his friend Capt. Jimmie Stuart.

title: Mount Fernow
description: The third highest non-volcanic peak in Washington state, located in the Entiat Mountains range, a sub range of the Cascades. Fernow, is flanked by many large glaciers and neighbors Bonanza Peak.

title: Goode Mountain
description: Named after topographer Richard Urquhart Goode, the mountain is the highest peak of the North Cascade national park. It is the fourth tallest non-volcanic peak in Washington.

title: Mount Shuksan
description: Getting its name from the Lummi word meaning 'high peak', located near to Mount Baker. The mountain is composed of oceanic basalt after the Easton terrane and North American coast collided 120 million years ago.

title: Buckner Mountain
description: The highest point in Skagit County as one of ten highest non-volcanic peaks in the state. Holds the third highest point in the North Cascade National Park.

title: Jack Mountain
description: Named by Henry Custer after Jack Rowley who was a prospector near the mountain. The mountain is located in Whatcom County, with a number of climbing routes along it's ridge

title: Mount Spickard
description: Part of the Skagit Range with two main drainage basins into the Skagit and Fraser rivers. The mountain was named after a climber who had passed when climbing the peak.

title: Black Peak
description: Got its name in 1926 after the first ascent was accomplished by Lage Wernsterdt. The mountain is part of the North Cascade range full of glaciers and glacial valleys.

title: Mount Redoubt
description: Located three miles away from the Canada-US border, in Whatcom county. The peak is next to Mount Spickard and is part of the Custer-Chillwack Group in the Skagit Range.

title: North Gardner Mountain
description: The 23rd highest peak in Washignton state, the mountain is located in the Okanogan-Wenatchee National Forest. Located within the North Cascade range on the east side of Washington state.

title: Dome Peak
description: Part of the Glacier Peak Wilderness in the North Cascades, the dome is a remote location in the range. The mountain has two main summits located in the southeast of Skagit County.

title: Silver Star Mountain
description: Part of a sub-range of the Cascades, standing within the Methow River which drains into the Columbia. The mountain is visible from the North Cascade Highway.

title: Eldorado Peak
description: The peak is in the North Cascade National Park surrounded by a number of glaciers. The peak is flanked by the larges continuous non-volcanic ice sheet.

title: Dragontail Peak
description: Named due to its resemblance of a dragon tail, the peak flanks Colchuck Lake. Dragon tail is the second highest peak in the Stuart range, second to Stuart Mountain

title: Oval Peak
description: Oval Peak is the highest peak in the Methow Mountain range which is a subrange of the North Cascades. A difficult climb for anyone looking to summit the peak. Oval Peak is characterized with a dryer climate compared to the rest of the area.

title: Mesahchie Peak
description: Named after the Chinook word for 'Wicked', the peak is the highest summit along the Ragged Ridge. The mountain itself is covered with glacial ice with major percipitation and rainfall in the colder seasons.
